the nearly instantaneous translation of texts by George Orwell, Thomas Mann, W. H. Auden, Richard Wright, Mary McCarthy, and Albert Camus, among others, into interrelated journals that were sponsored by organizations such as the CIA's Congress for Cultural Freedom and circulated around the world effectively reshaped writers, critics, and intellectuals into easily recognizable, transnational figures. Their work formed a new canon of world literature that was celebrated in the United States and supposedly represented the best of contemporary thought, while less politically attractive authors were ignored or even demonized. This championing and demonizing of writers occurred in the name of anti-Communism--the new, transatlantic "civilizing mission" through which postwar cultural and literary authority emerged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCold War in literature. 0aCriticismxHistoryx20th century. 0aCriticismxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican postwar ascendancy.  aCCF.  aCIA.  aCentral Intelligence Agency.  aCold War.  aCommunism.  aCongress for Cultural Freedom.  aEdward Said.  aErich Auerbach.  aFrankfurt School.  aFreedom of Information Act.  aGeorge Orwell.  aInstitute for Social Research.  aNineteen Eighty-Four.  aOrientalism.  aStephen Spender.  aTheodor Adorno.  aWorld War II.  aanticommunism.  acolonialism.  acultural diplomacy.  acultural domination.  acultural politics.  acultural space.  acultural translation.  acultural transmission.  adecolonization.  aempiricism.  aexile.  aexiled intellectual.  aglobal literary landscape.  aglobalization.  ahumanism.  ahumanistic practice.  aimperial authority.  ainstitutional challenges.  ajournals.  aknowledge suppression.  aliterary diplomacy. 